The paper focuses on developing optimization methods for clustering and partitioning problems, which are commonly studied in machine learning and data science. The learning-theoretic framework used in the paper suggests that it belongs to the cs.LG (Machine Learning) sub-category. Additionally, the paper discusses the complexity of algorithms used for these problems, which suggests that it could also belong to the cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.CC (Computational Complexity) sub-categories. The use of heuristics and approximation algorithms also suggests that it could belong to the cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) sub-category. Finally, the mention of SDP rounding algorithms and agglomerative clustering algorithms with dynamic programming suggests that it could belong to the cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) sub-category.
